members.docComment:
/**
 * Returns your order book for the stock market.
 *
 * This is an object containing information for all the Limit and Stop Orders you have in the stock market. The object has the following structure:
 * ```js
 * {
 *  StockSymbol1: [ // Array of orders for this stock
 *      {
 *          shares: Order quantity
 *          price: Order price
 *          type: Order type
 *          position: Either "L" or "S" for Long or Short position
 *      },
 *      {
 *          ...
 *      },
 *      ...
 *  ],
 *  StockSymbol2: [ // Array of orders for this stock
 *      ...
 *  ],
 *  ...
 * }
 * ```
 *
 * The Order type property can have one of the following four values: * Limit Buy Order * Limit Sell Order * Stop Buy Order * Stop Sell Order Note that the order book will only contain information for stocks that you actually have orders in.
 *
 * @remarks
 *
 * 2.5 GB
 *
 * @returns Object containing information for all the Limit and Stop Orders you have in the stock market.
 *
 * @example
 * ```js
 * "If you do not have orders in Nova Medical (NVMD), then the returned object will not have a NVMD property."
 * {
 *  ECP: [
 *      {
 *          shares: 5,
 *          price: 100,000
 *          type: "Stop Buy Order",
 *          position: "S",
 *      },
 *      {
 *          shares: 25,
 *          price: 125,000
 *          type: "Limit Sell Order",
 *          position: "L",
 *      },
 *  ],
 *  SYSC: [
 *      {
 *          shares: 100,
 *          price: 10,000
 *          type: "Limit Buy Order",
 *          position: "L",
 *      },
 *  ],
 * }
 * ```
 *
 */
members.name: getOrders

 *
 * The third element in the array is the number of shares the player owns of the stock in the Short position. The fourth element in the array is the average price of the players Short position.

/**
 * Attempts to sell shares of a stock using a Market Order.
 *
 * If the specified number of shares in the function exceeds the amount that the player actually owns, then this function will sell all owned shares. Remember that every transaction on the stock exchange costs a certain commission fee.
 *
 * The net profit made from selling stocks with this function is reflected in the scripts statistics. This net profit is calculated as:
 *
 * shares * (sell_price - average_price_of_purchased_shares)

 * If the sale is successful, this function will return the stock price at which each share was sold. Otherwise, it will return 0.
 *
 * @remarks
 *
 * 2.5 GB
